<br>
<br>
Bear with me for a minute and understand a little something. Cleircs and most who love the class have always loved two things about the class. 1) We heal/buff and we do it well, it has gotten us the groups we NEED to exp and as others close the gap we get territorial. It is the one thing we have for 3 years been able to count on allowing us a slot in a group. 2) This is where it gets tricky, We have remained a static and stable class for three years. Think about this for a second. With the advent of RoK, SoV and SoL, many classes went through role changes and clerics simply got upgrades to what they already do well (buff/heal). Our role and core abilities have not changed for three years. Us old clerics are getting set in our ways <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   .  With a slow encroachment on our most basic specialization (healing) and no real change to ourselves we natually feel threatened. <br>
<br>
Enter caster balancing. As Absor put it, it is coming in bits and pieces. I have seen this in the clerics already. Two little things come to mind. Tinkering with Judgement (I am still skeptical of the this actually being an improvement but, that is another thread entirely) and the change to Hammer of the Sun from a Dawncall proc to a right click Dawncall. I think the caster balancing for clerics means undead utility in the form of damage output and a limited form of buffs relating to undead ( lets face it Paladins and Necros have far outstripped clerics in dealing with undead). How does this affect druids? Well with even a decent change of role for clerics in groups this opens the door for healing improvement for druids in raids without infringing the ONLY role a cleric has to offer a group. In short, clerics find a second role they can fill in a group, healing is impoved for druids which helps raids and the bleed over into exp groups this healing will cause is marginalized by a cleric having a second role to fill when it comes to grouping and the ability to solo more effectivly.<br>
<br>
 I could be entirely off on this but, it seems to be heading this way by my reckoning. Looks like some of old clerics/dogs might have to learn some new tricks from you nice druid folk about versitilty in a group. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p><img src=http://eshamlin.home.mindspring.com/lith.jpg></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ulithahntalon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lith Ahntalon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0> at: 5/23/02 4:08:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucclothar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ccLothar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/23/02 7:16:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27401.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> re:</span><hr size=1> I've never seen a mob resist Warrior defensive.  On the other hand, there are tons of mobs that you can't Slow.<br>
