<br>
Example: every time someone mentions a DoT upgrade for druids, a bunch of number crunchers fly out of the woodwork to insist that shaman DoTs are &quot;supposed&quot; to be better than druids' and proceed to enumerate a list of DPS numbers.<br>
<br>
Supposed to be better? Says who? Sorry if I'm missing a page out of my EQ manual, but I've never read any rule stating that shamans are absolutely required to always have better DoTs than druids. <br>
<br>
Heck, if a better DoT would give druids a raid-beneficial, raid-critical role, that would be great -- shamans already own a raiding role (e.g. SLOW) and no class can effectively take that away from them. Unfortunately, unless they come up with something lure-based, a DoT upgrade isn't really going to bump druids up from last rung on the raid ladder.<br>
<br>
Example: every time someone mentions a healing upgrade for druids, some self-appointed spokesman for cleric justice comes along and complains that healing is the only thing they have to contribute, that druids have sow/snare/ports, blah blah blah, and if we're going to be versatile from 1st-50th level, we should pay for it 50+ by not being able to compete with clerics for grouping and raiding.<br>
<br>
Well by that logic, after 3 years of having a PERMANENT seat at every raid, maybe it's time for clerics to &quot;pay for it&quot; by giving up a little raid desirability to druids? :P<br>
<br>
Seriously, though, I'm amazed every time I hear a cleric shudder at the thought of not being first choice for every high end encounter. <br>
<br>
Attention Clerics ---<br>
If you don't show up, raid is cancelled! <br>
If druids had a 3khp heal, yet clerics didn't show up, raid would STILL be cancelled!<br>
<br>
Example: every time an upgrade to druid nukes is mentioned, someone comes along and complains that druids are a priest class not a damage class, and we better not dare ask for anything comparable to a wizard. <br>
<br>
Well, I'm not asking for manaburn, I'm not asking for a familiar, and I'm not asking for lure nukes. However, I don't see why two classes couldn't share in being the &quot;best&quot; at dealing spell-based damage. Actually, I rather like the idea that druids would be the undisputed top damage-dealers of the three priest classes (the other priest classes are *specialists* in support/healing), just as wizards are of Int casters (the other int casters are *specialists* in support/pets).<br>
<br>
Most of the folks who want druid healing improvements, emphasize the &quot;support healer&quot; role. Over time, though, it has become increasingly obvious that Verant doesn't consider &quot;support healer&quot; as a unique raiding role; and they have apparently decided that secondary role belongs to shamans -- think about it --Torpor is the perfect HoT to use on the raid's casters hit by incidental AoE, and on top of that, shamans already have the same spot heals as druids.<br>
<br>
I don't envy VI. What we refer to simply as &quot;caster balancing&quot; is a heck of a lot more complex than it appears on the surface. But I sincerely hope VI's developers won't allow themselves to be too heavily influenced by complaints made by the three caster classes who are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> already</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the most desirable casters for raiding. At best, it's a bit suspicious that any member of those particular classes would be so vehemently opposed to VI addressing problems with the druid class that have been largely neglected for two expansions.<br>
<br>
~Firemynd <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uspuzy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Spuzy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(5/24/02 1:30:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27401.topic&index=49>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Thoughts</span><hr size=1> You know, when I think of caster balancing, I compare classes within the groupings of classes, such as priest for Druids for example.  Need a port, ask a Druid, need a priest for an exp group, ask a Cleric or Shaman.  Pretty simple.  Porting has absolutely nothing to do with game encounters, it's just a convienance that is being nerfed by Verant to equate everyone.  SOL requires no ports, and Verant will continue to make it easier to get around without the need for ports.  Did I make a Druid solely to port, boy, what a fun existence that would be.  People who can two box make Druids simply to port, and nothing else.  Look at it from this perspective, does anyone who has any knowledge with EQ think that Druids are better then Clerics or Shamans?  It's fairly obvious that Clerics and Shamans are much better then Druids for 99.9% of any EQ encounter, now does that seem balanced?  To me, soloing means nothing, 90% of the game for me and for anyone in the &quot;end game&quot; is raiding.  Plain and simple.  <p>Cheers, <BR>
